# Anki Flashcard Tags and LATTE: A Study Method

-----

## How the System Works

The system works as a pipeline where each tool feeds the next, and the LATTE tags are the thread that ties everything together.

-----

## The Framework

LATTE splits every condition into six buckets:

|Bucket         |What It Covers                         |
|---------------|---------------------------------------|
|**Brief Patho**|What’s going wrong mechanically        |
|**Look**       |What you observe                       |
|**Assess**     |What you as the nurse do to gather data|
|**Tests**      |Labs / diagnostics                     |
|**Treatments** |Meds + nursing interventions           |
|**Educate**    |What you teach the patient             |

The v10c prompt forces every single card into exactly one bucket. This matters because nursing exams don’t test random facts — they test whether you can move through a clinical reasoning chain:

**patho → signs → assessment → diagnosis → intervention → teaching**

-----

## How the Tags Create Structure in Anki

When you import the cards, your Anki browser sidebar shows the tag hierarchy as a filterable tree:

```
Nursing::LATTE::BriefPatho
Nursing::LATTE::Look
Nursing::LATTE::Assess
Nursing::LATTE::Tests
Nursing::LATTE::Treatments
Nursing::LATTE::Educate
Condition::HeartFailure
Condition::COPD
Tier::1
Tier::2
Tier::3
```

You can click any combination to filter. That’s where the strategy comes in.

-----

## The Study Strategy

**Start with the tiers, not the LATTE buckets.** When you have 3 days before an exam, you don’t have time for everything.

- **Filter to `Tier::1` only** and review those until your retention is solid. That’s the 50–60% of cards covering safety-critical content, hallmark signs, priority interventions, major meds. **If you nail Tier 1, you pass.**
- **Tier 2 gets you a B.**
- **Tier 3 gets you the A** if time permits.

Once you’re in active review, **use LATTE filtering for weak-spot drilling:**

- Keep missing assessment questions on practice tests? Filter to `Nursing::LATTE::Assess` and hammer those.
- Pharmacology is your weak point? Filter `Nursing::LATTE::Treatments::Meds`.
- The tags let you isolate exactly the type of clinical reasoning you’re struggling with rather than reviewing everything blindly.

**The condition tags create a different axis.** Before a cardiac exam, filter `Condition::HeartFailure` and you see every card about HF — patho through education — in one filtered view. That’s your condition-level review. Walk through the LATTE sequence for that one condition: understand the mechanism, know the signs, know what to assess, know the labs, know the meds and interventions, know what to teach. That’s one complete clinical picture.

-----

## How the Full Pipeline Fits Together

|Step|Tool                     |Purpose                                                                                                                                                    |
|----|-------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
|1   |**Study Guide Generator**|The comprehensive reference document — your “textbook replacement” organized by LATTE. Read through it to build the big picture and understand connections.|
|2   |**Priority Analyzer**    |Tells you which parts of that guide are Tier 1 vs Tier 2 vs Tier 3, so you know where to spend your reading time.                                          |
|3   |**Anki Generator**       |Turns that content into atomic recall cards for spaced repetition.                                                                                         |
|4   |**NCLEX Extractor**      |Gives you practice questions to test application — can you actually use what you memorized in a clinical scenario?                                         |

The study sequence that gets the most out of all four:

> **Guide first** (read and understand) → **Priority Analyzer** (know what matters most) → **Anki cards** (memorize through spaced repetition) → **NCLEX questions** (test application)

**Don’t skip the reading step** — Anki without understanding is just memorizing words. The cards are designed to be fast because you’re supposed to already understand the concept; the card just keeps it from fading.

-----

## FSRS Tip

Since you’re using optimized FSRS settings for compressed study windows, the tier system pairs well with Anki’s custom study:

1. Create a filtered deck with `tag:Tier::1`
1. Set a high daily limit for the week before an exam
1. Let Tier 2 and 3 stay on their normal FSRS schedule

That way your algorithm is spending your review time proportionally to exam importance rather than treating every card equally.
